</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">The liver plays several complex but essential roles in the metabolism of amino acids, carbohydrates, and lipids, as well as synthesis of proteins. The basic pathophysiology of diffuse parenchymal hepatic diseases usually represents a failure in one of these metabolic pathways. Specific parenchymal diseases can be categorized as storage, vascular, and inflammatory diseases. Cross-sectional hepatic imaging techniques, specifically multidetector computed tomography (CT) and magnetic resonance (MR) imaging, have roles in evaluation of diffuse liver disease. The prominent role of multidetector CT is primarily defined by its excellent morphologic visualization capabilities, in particular of diffuse or focal intrahepatic lesions as well as of anatomic relationships between the liver and adjacent organs. The variety of available multidetector CT scanners covers a huge spectrum of detector configurations ranging from equally sized and equally spaced detector arrays to asymmetric detector configurations, resulting in imaging protocols with unique parameters for almost each multidetector CT system. In addition to 64–detector row imaging, hepatic multidetector CT can be performed with emerging techniques such as dual-energy CT. Hepatic MR imaging has been proved to be a comprehensive modality for assessing the morphology and functional characteristics of the liver. Concurrent technical improvements as well as implementation of advanced imaging sequence designs permit high-quality examination of the liver with T1-, T2-, and diffusion-weighted pulse sequences. Three basic demands remain if MR imaging is chosen for hepatic imaging: to improve parenchymal contrast, to suppress respiratory motion, and to ensure complete anatomic coverage. Supplemental material available at <i><a href="http://radiographics.rsna.org/content/29/6/1591/suppl/DC1">http://radiographics.rsna.org/content/29/6/1591/suppl/DC1</a></i>.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2009</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.296095513">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.296095513">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10a-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g10a.jpeg" height="1322" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f10a-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Diffusion-weighted image series obtained before <b>(a, b)</b> and after <b>(c, d)</b> administration of contrast material. The series consists of diffusion-weighted images obtained with a <i>b</i> value of 50 <b>(a, c)</b> and ADC maps <b>(b, d)</b>. On the postcontrast diffusion series, note the areas of signal void in the region of the renal collecting system (<b>*</b> in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>), which are related to T2* effects.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f10a-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10b-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g10b.jpeg" height="1320" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f10b-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Diffusion-weighted image series obtained before <b>(a, b)</b> and after <b>(c, d)</b> administration of contrast material. The series consists of diffusion-weighted images obtained with a <i>b</i> value of 50 <b>(a, c)</b> and ADC maps <b>(b, d)</b>. On the postcontrast diffusion series, note the areas of signal void in the region of the renal collecting system (<b>*</b> in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>), which are related to T2* effects.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f10b-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10c-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g10c.jpeg" height="1333" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f10c-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span> Diffusion-weighted image series obtained before <b>(a, b)</b> and after <b>(c, d)</b> administration of contrast material. The series consists of diffusion-weighted images obtained with a <i>b</i> value of 50 <b>(a, c)</b> and ADC maps <b>(b, d)</b>. On the postcontrast diffusion series, note the areas of signal void in the region of the renal collecting system (<b>*</b> in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>), which are related to T2* effects.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f10c-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10d-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g10d.jpeg" height="1320" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f10d-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10d</span> Diffusion-weighted image series obtained before <b>(a, b)</b> and after <b>(c, d)</b> administration of contrast material. The series consists of diffusion-weighted images obtained with a <i>b</i> value of 50 <b>(a, c)</b> and ADC maps <b>(b, d)</b>. On the postcontrast diffusion series, note the areas of signal void in the region of the renal collecting system (<b>*</b> in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>), which are related to T2* effects.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f10d-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11a-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g11a.jpeg" height="1553" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f11a-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Normal MR elastographic findings in a 24-year-old woman without known liver disease. Anatomic elastographic image <b>(a)</b>, wave image color-encoding the shear wavelength of physiologic liver parenchyma <b>(b)</b>, and elastographic image color-encoding the mean shear stiffness of physiologic liver parenchyma <b>(c)</b> show normal findings. (Case courtesy of Richard L. Ehman, MD, Mayo Clinic College of Medicine, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f11a-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11b-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23c11b.jpeg" height="1170" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f11b-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Normal MR elastographic findings in a 24-year-old woman without known liver disease. Anatomic elastographic image <b>(a)</b>, wave image color-encoding the shear wavelength of physiologic liver parenchyma <b>(b)</b>, and elastographic image color-encoding the mean shear stiffness of physiologic liver parenchyma <b>(c)</b> show normal findings. (Case courtesy of Richard L. Ehman, MD, Mayo Clinic College of Medicine, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f11b-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11c-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23c11c.jpeg" height="1161" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f11c-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span> Normal MR elastographic findings in a 24-year-old woman without known liver disease. Anatomic elastographic image <b>(a)</b>, wave image color-encoding the shear wavelength of physiologic liver parenchyma <b>(b)</b>, and elastographic image color-encoding the mean shear stiffness of physiologic liver parenchyma <b>(c)</b> show normal findings. (Case courtesy of Richard L. Ehman, MD, Mayo Clinic College of Medicine, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f11c-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f12a-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g12a.jpeg" height="1342" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f12a-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Abnormal MR elastographic findings in a 52-year-old man with known liver cirrhosis. Anatomic elastographic image <b>(a)</b>, wave image color-encoding the shear wavelength of cirrhotic liver parenchyma <b>(b)</b>, and elastographic image color-encoding the mean shear stiffness of cirrhotic liver parenchyma <b>(c)</b> show abnormal findings. Note the marked increase in mean shear stiffness compared with that of physiologic parenchyma. (Case courtesy of Richard L. Ehman, MD.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f12a-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f12b-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23c12b.jpeg" height="1051" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f12b-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Abnormal MR elastographic findings in a 52-year-old man with known liver cirrhosis. Anatomic elastographic image <b>(a)</b>, wave image color-encoding the shear wavelength of cirrhotic liver parenchyma <b>(b)</b>, and elastographic image color-encoding the mean shear stiffness of cirrhotic liver parenchyma <b>(c)</b> show abnormal findings. Note the marked increase in mean shear stiffness compared with that of physiologic parenchyma. (Case courtesy of Richard L. Ehman, MD.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f12b-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f12c-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23c12c.jpeg" height="1041" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f12c-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span> Abnormal MR elastographic findings in a 52-year-old man with known liver cirrhosis. Anatomic elastographic image <b>(a)</b>, wave image color-encoding the shear wavelength of cirrhotic liver parenchyma <b>(b)</b>, and elastographic image color-encoding the mean shear stiffness of cirrhotic liver parenchyma <b>(c)</b> show abnormal findings. Note the marked increase in mean shear stiffness compared with that of physiologic parenchyma. (Case courtesy of Richard L. Ehman, MD.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f12c-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f13-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g13x.jpeg" height="1306" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f13-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span> Biopsy-proved hepatic metastasis in a 31-year-old man. Contrast-enhanced T2-weighted MR image, obtained 60 minutes after administration of a ferumoxide-based contrast agent, shows a hepatic metastasis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f13-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f14a-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g14a.jpeg" height="1226" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f14a-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> T1-weighted MR images show the early arterial <b>(a)</b>, mid arterial <b>(b)</b>, and late arterial <b>(c)</b> phases of dynamic contrast-enhanced hepatic imaging.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f14a-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f14b-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g14b.jpeg" height="1237" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f14b-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> T1-weighted MR images show the early arterial <b>(a)</b>, mid arterial <b>(b)</b>, and late arterial <b>(c)</b> phases of dynamic contrast-enhanced hepatic imaging.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f14b-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f14c-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g14c.jpeg" height="1224" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f14c-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span> T1-weighted MR images show the early arterial <b>(a)</b>, mid arterial <b>(b)</b>, and late arterial <b>(c)</b> phases of dynamic contrast-enhanced hepatic imaging.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f14c-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f15-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g15x.jpeg" height="1438" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f15-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span> Hepatic adenomas in a 19-year-old man with type Ia (von Gierke) glycogen storage disease. Contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image, obtained during the late arterial phase after administration of a gadolinium-based contrast agent, shows large (arrowhead) and small (arrow) hepatic adenomas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f15-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f16-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g16x.jpeg" height="1442" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f16-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span> Niemann-Pick disease in an 11-year-old girl. Portal venous phase image from contrast-enhanced multidetector CT shows hepatomegaly and splenomegaly.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f16-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f17-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g17x.jpeg" height="1360" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f17-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span> Type I (Hurler) mucopolysaccharidosis in a 19-year-old man. Contrast-enhanced hepatic MR image shows extended cirrhosis and an area of conflu-ent fibrosis (arrow). Ascites and splenomegaly are also present.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f17-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f18-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g18x.jpeg" height="1194" width="1601" aria-labelledby="f18-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span> Acute viral hepatitis in a 39-year-old man. Arterial phase image from contrast-enhanced multidetector CT shows heterogeneous enhancement (arrows) of the edematous enlarged liver.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f18-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1a-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g01a.jpeg" height="1201" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f1a-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Fatty infiltration of the liver parenchyma in a 46-year-old woman with ovarian cancer who was undergoing chemotherapy. Sequential nonenhanced <b>(a–c)</b> and portal venous perfusion phase contrast material–enhanced <b>(d–f)</b> images from multidetector CT, obtained at 3-month intervals, show a progressive decrease in hepatic attenuation. Circle = region of interest, number = attenuation in Hounsfield units.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f1a-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1b-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g01b.jpeg" height="1292" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f1b-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Fatty infiltration of the liver parenchyma in a 46-year-old woman with ovarian cancer who was undergoing chemotherapy. Sequential nonenhanced <b>(a–c)</b> and portal venous perfusion phase contrast material–enhanced <b>(d–f)</b> images from multidetector CT, obtained at 3-month intervals, show a progressive decrease in hepatic attenuation. Circle = region of interest, number = attenuation in Hounsfield units.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f1b-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1c-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g01c.jpeg" height="1250" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f1c-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span> Fatty infiltration of the liver parenchyma in a 46-year-old woman with ovarian cancer who was undergoing chemotherapy. Sequential nonenhanced <b>(a–c)</b> and portal venous perfusion phase contrast material–enhanced <b>(d–f)</b> images from multidetector CT, obtained at 3-month intervals, show a progressive decrease in hepatic attenuation. Circle = region of interest, number = attenuation in Hounsfield units.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f1c-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1d-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g01d.jpeg" height="1143" width="1656" aria-labelledby="f1d-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1d</span> Fatty infiltration of the liver parenchyma in a 46-year-old woman with ovarian cancer who was undergoing chemotherapy. Sequential nonenhanced <b>(a–c)</b> and portal venous perfusion phase contrast material–enhanced <b>(d–f)</b> images from multidetector CT, obtained at 3-month intervals, show a progressive decrease in hepatic attenuation. Circle = region of interest, number = attenuation in Hounsfield units.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f1d-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1e-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g01e.jpeg" height="1255" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f1e-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1e</span> Fatty infiltration of the liver parenchyma in a 46-year-old woman with ovarian cancer who was undergoing chemotherapy. Sequential nonenhanced <b>(a–c)</b> and portal venous perfusion phase contrast material–enhanced <b>(d–f)</b> images from multidetector CT, obtained at 3-month intervals, show a progressive decrease in hepatic attenuation. Circle = region of interest, number = attenuation in Hounsfield units.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f1e-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1f-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g01f.jpeg" height="1223" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f1f-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1f</span> Fatty infiltration of the liver parenchyma in a 46-year-old woman with ovarian cancer who was undergoing chemotherapy. Sequential nonenhanced <b>(a–c)</b> and portal venous perfusion phase contrast material–enhanced <b>(d–f)</b> images from multidetector CT, obtained at 3-month intervals, show a progressive decrease in hepatic attenuation. Circle = region of interest, number = attenuation in Hounsfield units.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f1f-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f2-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g02x.jpeg" height="1300" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f2-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span> Histologically proved Wilson disease in a 41-year-old man. Nonenhanced image from multidetector CT shows increased attenuation of the hepatic parenchyma. Circle = region of interest, number = attenuation in Hounsfield units.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f2-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3a-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g03a.jpeg" height="1361" width="1674" aria-labelledby="f3a-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Histologically confirmed mild steatosis hepatis in a 52-year-old man. The patient underwent contrast-enhanced dual-energy multidetector CT. <b>(a, b)</b> Images obtained at 140 kVp <b>(a)</b> and 80 kVp <b>(b)</b> show no apparent steatosis. Arrow in <b>b</b>, <b>c</b>, and <b>d</b> indicates the margins of the smaller field of view of the 80-kVp scan. <b>(c)</b> Image shows the results of dual-energy multidetector CT–based iodine extraction. <b>(d)</b> Image shows the subsequently calculated subtraction data set. The attenuation values are consistent with mild steatosis hepatis. Small circle in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b> = region of interest, number in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b> = attenuation in Hounsfield units. <b>(e)</b> Previously obtained nonenhanced CT image shows attenuation values comparable with those in <b>d</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f3a-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3b-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g03b.jpeg" height="1506" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f3b-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Histologically confirmed mild steatosis hepatis in a 52-year-old man. The patient underwent contrast-enhanced dual-energy multidetector CT. <b>(a, b)</b> Images obtained at 140 kVp <b>(a)</b> and 80 kVp <b>(b)</b> show no apparent steatosis. Arrow in <b>b</b>, <b>c</b>, and <b>d</b> indicates the margins of the smaller field of view of the 80-kVp scan. <b>(c)</b> Image shows the results of dual-energy multidetector CT–based iodine extraction. <b>(d)</b> Image shows the subsequently calculated subtraction data set. The attenuation values are consistent with mild steatosis hepatis. Small circle in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b> = region of interest, number in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b> = attenuation in Hounsfield units. <b>(e)</b> Previously obtained nonenhanced CT image shows attenuation values comparable with those in <b>d</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f3b-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3c-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g03c.jpeg" height="1511" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f3c-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span> Histologically confirmed mild steatosis hepatis in a 52-year-old man. The patient underwent contrast-enhanced dual-energy multidetector CT. <b>(a, b)</b> Images obtained at 140 kVp <b>(a)</b> and 80 kVp <b>(b)</b> show no apparent steatosis. Arrow in <b>b</b>, <b>c</b>, and <b>d</b> indicates the margins of the smaller field of view of the 80-kVp scan. <b>(c)</b> Image shows the results of dual-energy multidetector CT–based iodine extraction. <b>(d)</b> Image shows the subsequently calculated subtraction data set. The attenuation values are consistent with mild steatosis hepatis. Small circle in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b> = region of interest, number in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b> = attenuation in Hounsfield units. <b>(e)</b> Previously obtained nonenhanced CT image shows attenuation values comparable with those in <b>d</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f3c-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3d-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g03d.jpeg" height="1437" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f3d-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span> Histologically confirmed mild steatosis hepatis in a 52-year-old man. The patient underwent contrast-enhanced dual-energy multidetector CT. <b>(a, b)</b> Images obtained at 140 kVp <b>(a)</b> and 80 kVp <b>(b)</b> show no apparent steatosis. Arrow in <b>b</b>, <b>c</b>, and <b>d</b> indicates the margins of the smaller field of view of the 80-kVp scan. <b>(c)</b> Image shows the results of dual-energy multidetector CT–based iodine extraction. <b>(d)</b> Image shows the subsequently calculated subtraction data set. The attenuation values are consistent with mild steatosis hepatis. Small circle in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b> = region of interest, number in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b> = attenuation in Hounsfield units. <b>(e)</b> Previously obtained nonenhanced CT image shows attenuation values comparable with those in <b>d</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f3d-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3e-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g03e.jpeg" height="1510" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f3e-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3e</span> Histologically confirmed mild steatosis hepatis in a 52-year-old man. The patient underwent contrast-enhanced dual-energy multidetector CT. <b>(a, b)</b> Images obtained at 140 kVp <b>(a)</b> and 80 kVp <b>(b)</b> show no apparent steatosis. Arrow in <b>b</b>, <b>c</b>, and <b>d</b> indicates the margins of the smaller field of view of the 80-kVp scan. <b>(c)</b> Image shows the results of dual-energy multidetector CT–based iodine extraction. <b>(d)</b> Image shows the subsequently calculated subtraction data set. The attenuation values are consistent with mild steatosis hepatis. Small circle in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b> = region of interest, number in <b>d</b> and <b>e</b> = attenuation in Hounsfield units. <b>(e)</b> Previously obtained nonenhanced CT image shows attenuation values comparable with those in <b>d</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f3e-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f4-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g04x.jpeg" height="1421" width="1692" aria-labelledby="f4-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span> Histologically confirmed steatosis hepatis in a 49-year-old woman. Combined image from dual-energy multidetector CT shows weighted and fused 140-kVp and 80-kVp image data sets. Artifacts caused by differing fields of view for high-energy and low-energy data acquisition (arrows) might lead to misinterpretation. Hepatic subcapsular steatosis developing in response to intraperitoneal insulin delivery might have a similar appearance at dual-energy multidetector CT. However, only the dual-energy multidetector CT artifact can be seen in contralateral abdominal structures such as the spleen (<b>*</b>) as well (<a href="#b8-0291591" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="b8-0291591">8</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f4-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5a-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g05a.jpeg" height="1171" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f5a-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Normal findings in a 41-year-old woman without known liver disease. In-phase <b>(a)</b>, opposed-phase <b>(b)</b>, water-only <b>(c)</b>, and fat-only <b>(d)</b> T1-weighted two-point Dixon MR images show a normal appearance of the liver.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f5a-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5b-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g05b.jpeg" height="1210" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f5b-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Normal findings in a 41-year-old woman without known liver disease. In-phase <b>(a)</b>, opposed-phase <b>(b)</b>, water-only <b>(c)</b>, and fat-only <b>(d)</b> T1-weighted two-point Dixon MR images show a normal appearance of the liver.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f5b-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5c-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g05c.jpeg" height="1199" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f5c-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span> Normal findings in a 41-year-old woman without known liver disease. In-phase <b>(a)</b>, opposed-phase <b>(b)</b>, water-only <b>(c)</b>, and fat-only <b>(d)</b> T1-weighted two-point Dixon MR images show a normal appearance of the liver.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f5c-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5d-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g05d.jpeg" height="1193" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f5d-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5d</span> Normal findings in a 41-year-old woman without known liver disease. In-phase <b>(a)</b>, opposed-phase <b>(b)</b>, water-only <b>(c)</b>, and fat-only <b>(d)</b> T1-weighted two-point Dixon MR images show a normal appearance of the liver.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f5d-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6a-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g06a.jpeg" height="1203" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f6a-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Histologically confirmed steatosis hepatis in a 49-year-old man. In-phase <b>(a)</b>, opposed-phase <b>(b)</b>, water-only <b>(c)</b>, and fat-only <b>(d)</b> T1-weighted two-point Dixon MR images show steatosis hepatis, which appears as a drop in signal intensity on the opposed-phase image (cf <a href="#f5b-0291591">Fig 5b</a>) and a marked increase in signal intensity on the fat-only image (cf <a href="#f5d-0291591">Fig 5d</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f6a-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6b-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g06b.jpeg" height="1209" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f6b-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Histologically confirmed steatosis hepatis in a 49-year-old man. In-phase <b>(a)</b>, opposed-phase <b>(b)</b>, water-only <b>(c)</b>, and fat-only <b>(d)</b> T1-weighted two-point Dixon MR images show steatosis hepatis, which appears as a drop in signal intensity on the opposed-phase image (cf <a href="#f5b-0291591">Fig 5b</a>) and a marked increase in signal intensity on the fat-only image (cf <a href="#f5d-0291591">Fig 5d</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f6b-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6c-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g06c.jpeg" height="1203" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f6c-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span> Histologically confirmed steatosis hepatis in a 49-year-old man. In-phase <b>(a)</b>, opposed-phase <b>(b)</b>, water-only <b>(c)</b>, and fat-only <b>(d)</b> T1-weighted two-point Dixon MR images show steatosis hepatis, which appears as a drop in signal intensity on the opposed-phase image (cf <a href="#f5b-0291591">Fig 5b</a>) and a marked increase in signal intensity on the fat-only image (cf <a href="#f5d-0291591">Fig 5d</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f6c-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6d-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g06d.jpeg" height="1197" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f6d-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6d</span> Histologically confirmed steatosis hepatis in a 49-year-old man. In-phase <b>(a)</b>, opposed-phase <b>(b)</b>, water-only <b>(c)</b>, and fat-only <b>(d)</b> T1-weighted two-point Dixon MR images show steatosis hepatis, which appears as a drop in signal intensity on the opposed-phase image (cf <a href="#f5b-0291591">Fig 5b</a>) and a marked increase in signal intensity on the fat-only image (cf <a href="#f5d-0291591">Fig 5d</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f6d-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7a-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g07a.jpeg" height="1244" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f7a-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Histologically confirmed hepatic iron deposition in a 72-year-old man. In-phase <b>(a)</b>, opposed-phase <b>(b)</b>, water-only <b>(c)</b>, and fat-only <b>(d)</b> T1-weighted two-point Dixon MR images show hepatic iron deposition as a drop in signal intensity on the in-phase image (cf <a href="#f5a-0291591">Fig 5a</a>). There is a marked but artifactual increase in signal intensity on the fat-only image (cf <a href="#f5d-0291591">Fig 5d</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f7a-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7b-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g07b.jpeg" height="1237" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f7b-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Histologically confirmed hepatic iron deposition in a 72-year-old man. In-phase <b>(a)</b>, opposed-phase <b>(b)</b>, water-only <b>(c)</b>, and fat-only <b>(d)</b> T1-weighted two-point Dixon MR images show hepatic iron deposition as a drop in signal intensity on the in-phase image (cf <a href="#f5a-0291591">Fig 5a</a>). There is a marked but artifactual increase in signal intensity on the fat-only image (cf <a href="#f5d-0291591">Fig 5d</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f7b-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7c-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g07c.jpeg" height="1265" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f7c-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span> Histologically confirmed hepatic iron deposition in a 72-year-old man. In-phase <b>(a)</b>, opposed-phase <b>(b)</b>, water-only <b>(c)</b>, and fat-only <b>(d)</b> T1-weighted two-point Dixon MR images show hepatic iron deposition as a drop in signal intensity on the in-phase image (cf <a href="#f5a-0291591">Fig 5a</a>). There is a marked but artifactual increase in signal intensity on the fat-only image (cf <a href="#f5d-0291591">Fig 5d</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f7c-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7d-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g07d.jpeg" height="1235" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f7d-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span> Histologically confirmed hepatic iron deposition in a 72-year-old man. In-phase <b>(a)</b>, opposed-phase <b>(b)</b>, water-only <b>(c)</b>, and fat-only <b>(d)</b> T1-weighted two-point Dixon MR images show hepatic iron deposition as a drop in signal intensity on the in-phase image (cf <a href="#f5a-0291591">Fig 5a</a>). There is a marked but artifactual increase in signal intensity on the fat-only image (cf <a href="#f5d-0291591">Fig 5d</a>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f7d-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f8-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g08x.jpeg" height="1800" width="1381" aria-labelledby="f8-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span> Coronal single-shot fast spin-echo T2-weighted image shows the entire abdomen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f8-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f9-0291591" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.296095513/asset/images/g09oc23g09x.jpeg" height="1300" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f9-0291591" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span> Axial image of the porta hepatis, obtained by using true fast imaging with steady-state precession, shows cavernous transformation of the portal vein.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.296095513&amp;id=f9-0291591">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="b1-0291591" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Kamel IR, Kruskal JB, Pomfret EA, Keogan MT, Warmbrand G, Raptopoulos V. Impact of multidetector CT on donor selection and surgical planning before living adult right lobe liver transplantation. <em>AJR Am J Roentgenol</em> 2001;176:193–200.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.2214/ajr.176.1.1760193">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11133565/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Impact+of+multidetector+CT+on+donor+selection+and+surgical+planning+before+living+adult+right+lobe+liver+transplantation&amp;author=IR+Kamel&amp;author=JB+Kruskal&amp;author=EA+Pomfret&amp;author=MT+Keogan&amp;author=G+Warmbrand&amp;author=V+Raptopoulos&amp;publication_year=2001&amp;journal=AJR+Am+J+Roentgenol&amp;pages=193-200&amp;doi=10.2214%2Fajr.176.1.1760193&amp;pmid=11133565">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="b2-0291591" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Flohr TG, McCollough CH, Bruder H, et al. First performance evaluation of a dual-source CT (DSCT) system. <em>Eur Radiol</em> 2006;16:256–268.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/s00330-005-2919-2">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16341833/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=First+performance+evaluation+of+a+dual-source+CT+%28DSCT%29+system&amp;author=TG+Flohr&amp;author=CH+McCollough&amp;author=H+Bruder&amp;publication_year=2006&amp;journal=Eur+Radiol&amp;pages=256-268&amp;doi=10.1007%2Fs00330-005-2919-2&amp;pmid=16341833">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="b3-0291591" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Dwyer A, Doppman JL, Adams AJ, Girton ME, Chernick SS, Cornblath M. Influence of glycogen on liver density: computed tomography from a metabolic perspective. <em>J Comput Assist Tomogr</em> 1983;7:70–73.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/0000472